21:23.649 --> 21:25.151 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Tad Devine, we thank you.

21:25.151 --> 21:27.186 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TAD DEVINE: Thank you, Judy.

21:27.186 --> 21:30.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And to
the Republican side.

21:30.523 --> 21:35.761 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tom Rath is senior national
adviser to Governor John Kasich.
He's also in Manchester.

21:35.761 --> 21:38.397 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Tom Rath, thanks very much.

21:38.397 --> 21:44.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we know Governor Kasich has
spent a lot of time, invested a
lot of his effort in the

21:44.003 --> 21:49.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
state of New Hampshire. You hear
prognosticators say that he's
either got to come in second

21:49.275 --> 21:51.410 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
or a very strong
third, given that.

21:51.410 --> 21:53.879 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Will he?

21:53.879 --> 21:58.584 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
THOMAS RATH, John Kasich
Campaign Senior Adviser: Well,
look it, Judy, I think this is
such

21:58.584 --> 22:02.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an incredibly different election
than any one I have ever seen
that I'm not willing

22:02.821 --> 22:06.792 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to put a do-or-die on any
particular position.

22:06.792 --> 22:11.664 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think what candidates have to
do here is establish that they
are credible and that

22:11.664 --> 22:16.835 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they can attract a significant
portion of the electorate.
Frankly, I believe the polling

22:16.835 --> 22:23.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has Donald Trump up around 30,
and then from about numbers two
through numbers six, you

22:23.809 --> 22:26.745 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
can cover them with a
blanket. It's that close.

22:26.745 --> 22:32.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I don't know what that will
say if you miss your mark by a
point or if you overperform

22:32.551 --> 22:37.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by a point. I just think this is
a very close race that's going
to come down to the end.

22:37.156 --> 22:41.694 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I do not see the middle
coalescing behind anybody at
this point.

22:41.694 --> 22:45.497 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let me ask
you about that, because one of
your competitors, Senator

22:45.497 --> 22:50.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Marco Rubio, was seen as having
a tough time in that Republican
debate Saturday night.

22:50.736 --> 22:55.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you look at that as a -- just
his being knocked off his game
for a few days, or did

22:55.507 --> 22:58.811 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that do more lasting
damage to him?

22:58.811 --> 23:05.251 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
THOMAS RATH: Well, the problem
with that is, in the world we
live in, it's YouTube and

23:05.251 --> 23:08.020 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
videotape loops.

23:08.020 --> 23:15.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Marco Rubio's problem goes
beyond that. He has tried to be
in two lanes at once. And

23:15.494 --> 23:20.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's why, when you get into a
question that throws him off the
talking points, he's got

23:20.799 --> 23:24.937 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to remember who he's going to
orient himself to, whether it's
the hard right, the ideologic

23:24.937 --> 23:28.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
right, as he did at the end with
his abortion questions, or does
he come across more as

23:28.474 --> 23:30.943 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
somebody who can bring
people together?

23:30.943 --> 23:37.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is really what threw him
off. That will stay with him
long after the back-and-forth

23:37.916 --> 23:42.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
goes on, although, as I said
before, those kind of things,
like "Oops" for Governor Perry,

23:42.454 --> 23:44.957 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
tend to stay with
you a long time.

23:44.957 --> 23:48.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I want to also
ask you about Jeb Bush. Governor
Kasich has been lumped

23:48.961 --> 23:54.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in with this group of governors
seen as moderate who are
competing with each other to
achieve

23:54.333 --> 23:57.436 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
liftoff.

23:57.436 --> 24:01.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Who's going to come in ahead,
Governor Kasich or Governor
Bush?

24:01.507 --> 24:05.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
THOMAS RATH: I think we have a
really good chance to prevail.
We have worked very, very

24:05.344 --> 24:10.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hard here and we have got a good
ground game. I, for months, have
said I do not believe

24:10.249 --> 24:14.153 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the reports of the demise
of Jeb Bush's campaign.

24:14.153 --> 24:18.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's a good candidate. He's
well-thought-of here. His
campaign has done well. I think

24:18.891 --> 24:23.696 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it's a real battle for us with
them. I think, in the end, we're
going to finish ahead of

24:23.696 --> 24:27.132 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them. But I'm not going to take
that to the bank there. We have
got a lot of work to do

24:27.132 --> 24:30.669 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
between now and 8:00
tomorrow night.

24:30.669 --> 24:35.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally, Tom
Rath, let me ask you about that
group of voters, the
undeclareds,

24:35.007 --> 24:38.944 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the independents in New
Hampshire. They can vote in
either party. What do you expect
them

24:38.944 --> 24:41.547 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to do?

24:41.547 --> 24:47.519 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
THOMAS RATH: Well, I think
they're going to do what they
usually do, which is, at some

24:47.519 --> 24:51.523 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
point, mystically, they make a
decision and they all go en
masse to one or the other.

24:51.523 --> 24:54.693 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's like they send a secret
message out or something.

24:54.693 --> 25:01.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It happened with McCain twice.
And I think it sort of happened
with Hillary Clinton the

25:01.633 --> 25:07.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
last time. They are hard to
predict. They are terribly
engaged. We did one of the last

25:07.840 --> 25:11.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
town halls with Governor Kasich
this morning, and one woman who
was undeclared said this

25:11.243 --> 25:14.513 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
