she had seen him.

25:14.513 --> 25:16.949 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, they're paying attention.
And we hope to get a good share
of them.

25:16.949 --> 25:20.052 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: No prediction?

25:20.052 --> 25:24.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
THOMAS RATH: I think we are
going to do all right. I would
say two, three would be a very

25:24.590 --> 25:29.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
acceptable result. And I think
we could even do -- we could
probably even be stronger in

25:29.061 --> 25:32.731 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
terms of separation, if
things broke right for us.

25:32.731 --> 25:36.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Tom Rath, who is
working hard for Governor John
Kasich, we thank you so

25:36.068 --> 25:36.835 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
much.

25:36.835 --> 25:40.139 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
THOMAS RATH: Thank you, Judy.

25:40.139 --> 25:45.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The eve of the New
Hampshire primary is the perfect
time for Politics Monday.

25:45.778 --> 25:48.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm joined by Tamara Keith of
NPR in Manchester, New
Hampshire, and Amy Walter of The
Cook

25:48.914 --> 25:51.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Political Report.

25:51.917 --> 25:56.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Amy -- Tamara, I'm going to
start with you, because you are
sitting in the cold in
Manchester,

25:56.655 --> 26:01.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
New Hampshire. And you're
covering up close what looks to
me like a collision between

26:01.260 --> 26:06.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
gender politics and generational
politics involving Bernie
Sanders and Hillary Clinton,

26:06.365 --> 26:10.536 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but mostly self-inflicted wounds
from Hillary Clinton's people.

26:10.536 --> 26:15.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH, National Public
Radio: Absolutely. Her
surrogates and supporters said
some things

26:15.507 --> 26:21.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that are not going to make young
feminists happy, that have upset
young feminists, in

26:21.046 --> 26:25.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fact, and it sort of counter to
the message that Hillary Clinton
herself has been trying

26:25.884 --> 26:30.622 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to get out there, which is, I
know that young women support
Bernie Sanders, but, she hopes,

26:30.622 --> 26:34.393 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
she says, to win them over.

26:34.393 --> 26:40.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is not a new collision
among young feminists and older
feminists. It played out in
2008,

26:40.499 --> 26:42.935 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and it's happening again.

26:42.935 --> 26:48.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Amy, did Gloria
Steinem and Madeleine Albright
step in it?

26:48.040 --> 26:51.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMY WALTER, The Cook Political
Report: By -- trying to shame
women into supporting a

26:51.977 --> 26:56.682 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
woman is not usually the
best way to entice someone.

26:56.682 --> 26:58.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's what I find, personally,
especially when you're a
candidate. That's not the best

26:58.884 --> 26:59.151 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
way to get somebody
to vote for you.

26:59.151 --> 27:00.686 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
GWEN IFILL: Yes.

27:00.686 --> 27:03.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMY WALTER: But I do want to
make a really important
distinction, which is we're
talking

27:03.956 --> 27:08.627 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about women in New Hampshire and
Iowa right now who are
overwhelmingly white.

27:08.627 --> 27:13.198 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When you look at how Bernie
Sanders does in New Hampshire
and Iowa among young people,

27:13.198 --> 27:18.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
huge gap. But when I went and
looked at the polls that were
taken in South Carolina, which

27:18.036 --> 27:22.608 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
is a much more diverse
electorate, Hillary Clinton
holds her own among younger
voters.

27:22.608 --> 27:28.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what I'm very curious to see
is if this generational gender
collision continues once

27:28.180 --> 27:31.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
we get into states that
are a lot more diverse.

27:31.917 --> 27:37.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That said, it's the challenge
that Hillary Clinton has had
really since 2008, which,

27:37.956 --> 27:44.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is you know, they say you like
to campaign in poetry and govern
in prose. She campaigns

27:44.329 --> 27:48.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in prose and governs in prose.
And there is very little poetry
there and. We saw that

27:48.901 --> 27:51.937 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
poetry problem again this week.

27:51.937 --> 27:55.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Tam, let's stick
with the Clintons for a moment,
because Bill Clinton, who is

27:55.641 --> 28:01.613 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
no stranger of the highways and
byways of the Manchester
pre-primary, came out last

28:01.613 --> 28:05.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
night and said some pretty hard
thing. He kind of piled on and
seemed kind of irritated

28:05.217 --> 28:09.688 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at the idea that Bernie Sanders
would criticize his wife.

28:09.688 --> 28:14.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: Yes, I think that
Bill Clinton feels like Bernie
Sanders has had sort of

28:14.960 --> 28:21.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a garden path here, that Bernie
Sanders hasn't been put to the
same scrutiny as Hillary
Clinton.

28:21.099 --> 28:24.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it seems like Bill Clinton
is saying, all right, well, if
nobody else is going to

28:24.303 --> 28:29.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
do it, I'm going to do it. And,
again, it's not clear how well
this is going to play.

28:29.241 --> 28:35.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Sanders camp and Sanders
supporters are pretty upset with
Bill Clinton. Of course,

28:35.714 --> 28:38.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that is Bill Clinton's right to
do that, and he did something --
some similar things in

28:38.884 --> 28:41.053 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
2008.

28:41.053 --> 28:47.426 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that, as it's clear that
Hillary Clinton is going to have
a -- I mean, she's, in all

28:47.426 --> 28:52.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
likelihood, not going to win
here, and not even close, as
it's clear that she has a
tougher

28:52.097 --> 28:56.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
path. I think Bill Clinton is --
as they say, the big dog might
be getting off leash a little

28:56.568 --> 28:58.470 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
bit.

28:58.470 --> 29:02.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Boy, it feels like
we have had that very
conversation, 2008 especially.
And

29:02.708 --> 29:06.645 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that was when he was critical of
Barack Obama for the same
reason, saying that he felt like

29:06.645 --> 29:06.979 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
he hadn't gotten
enough scrutiny.

29:06.979 --> 29:07.112 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

29:07.112 --> 29:08.947 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
AMY WALTER: Right.

29:08.947 --> 29:13.118 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But let's move to
the Republicans. Saturday night,
big debate in the old town,

29:13.118 --> 29:18.223 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Marco Rubio was generally
seen initially as not having
done terribly well because he

29:18.223 --> 29:23.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
came off as somewhat robotic.
Was that real or was that kind
of overblown, Amy?

29:23.195 --> 29:25.797 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AMY WALTER: Well, we're going to
know a lot more tomorrow night.

29:25.797 --> 29:27.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Yes. Yes.

29:27.766 --> 29:32.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, look, I think that where
Marco Rubio was headed before
that debate was on a big

29:32.371 --> 29:37.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wave of momentum after Iowa.
When you talked to people
privately, they said they could

29:37.075 --> 29:43.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see his numbers move up in New
Hampshire. It was all about
closing strongly, right,

29:43.148 --> 29:46.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
